But it is doubtful whether peratralia Vestae could thus be used of a private house, even though there was usually an altar to Vesta on the hearth. Besides this separates the words too mech in thought from invita recedant; it is better to render ‘although they may be reluctant to retire, and may still cling to the sanctuary of Vesta‘s lane'. In the temple of Vesta there were certain mysterious objects‚ accessible only to the Vestals and the Pontiffs and carefully kept from the eyes ol the multi· tude: they were kept in the penus interior or penetrale of the temple, shut up in earthen vessels, and were regarded as the pignora imperii (le. xxvr. 27, Ovid‚ Fast. vr. 359, 439).
